description:
When I was a young boy (1950's), I learned to play golf by closely watching the best players at the course I grew up on. I would then stand in front of a window and copy their swings... then I would go to the practice area to ingrain that look and new feeling to muscle memory. That WAS and STILL IS a great way to learn! It's called SELF-DISCOVERY! 

When you discover a helpful motion or thought ALL BY YOURSELF, YOU WILL NEVER FORGET IT! - I never have!  

At the age of 78, I'm still a mid single-digit player. My goal with this YouTube channel is to provide a platform for TEACHING and LEARNING! I will provide videos and detailed descriptions of the finest golfers in the world, their swings and some of their finest shots so YOU can learn and improve as I have. 

The focus here is geared toward TEACHING and LEARNING the short game (putting, chipping, pitching and wedge play from 120-yards in), but you will also see some of the finest, Tour-Proven full swings and descriptions as well.⛳️

for about 12 years, I started doing short films and tests with an old Hi8 Sony Camera!

Ross Rich, DVM, PA-C. The hospital is located on five acres just north of the Carefree Highway in Phoenix, Arizona. The facility offers medical and surgical services geared towards diagnosis and treatment of sports-related problems in the elite equine athlete, as well as the future equine athlete (the young horse). Orthopedic and respiratory issues continue to be Cave Creek Equine Surgical & Diagnostic Imaging Center's primary interest and focus. However, we also deal with other soft tissue problems in the equine athlete. Cave Creek Equine Surgical & Diagnostic Imaging Center strives to keep the veterinarians, technicians, and office staff updated in the most innovative care of the horse from the beloved pet to international competition horse.

description:
Since many years I am a wildlife filmer with passion. If I watch an animal in the wild, it makes me happy. However, I am not a "classical wildlife filmer ". I don't sit for days on the high seat of a hunter and I don't spend my time in a camouflage tent for a good recording. My way to film animals is the "safari" method. I move slowly and carefully through the nature like a Bushman in the Kalahari. In this way I have filmed 151 species.

Seit vielen Jahren bin ich Tierfilmer aus Leidenschaft. Wenn ich ein Tier in der Wildnis beobachten kann, macht mich das glücklich. Allerdings bin ich kein "klassischer Tierfilmer". Ich setze mich nicht für eine gute Aufnahme tagelang auf den Hochsitz eines Jägers und ich verbringe meine Zeit auch nicht in einem Tarnzelt. Meine Art Tiere zu filmen ist eher die "Safarimethode". Ich bewege mich im Pirschgang langsam und vorsichtig durch die Natur wie ein Buschmann in der Kalahari. Auf diese Weise habe ich inzwischen 151 verschiedene Tierarten gefilmt.

description:
Gaye DeRusso began her career as a professional horse trainer in the 1990's. She then went back to school and worked as an Orthopedic Physician Assistant for over 20 years. 

She began her journey with  gaited horses in the year 2000.  Since that time, she has been an advocate for the gaited horse to gait naturally. Due to her background in Orthopedics, she also enjoys helping Veternarians  that  do not understand  the intricacies of how gaited horse move. 

Realizing many gaited horses  have very little training.  Gaye decided to go on a mission to  help the owners of gaited horses improve their horsemanship skills as well as their horse's basic training, and gaits.

Gaye, also known as The Majestic Rider, runs a comprehensive training program in Royal Oaks, Ca. She trains and sells many different breeds of  gaited horses. 

Her skills set her apart from other gaited trainers.  See her website for more information and many helpful articles on the gaited horse  www.majesticrider.com

description: This channel highlights the work of Texas Christian University's Locomotor Performance Lab (LPL).  The LPL specializes in terrestrial locomotion and in relating muscle function to metabolic energy expenditure and performance. Current research focuses on the relationships between the mechanics of movement, performance, metabolic energy expenditure, and metabolic power. This research addresses scientific questions at the whole-body or organism level of biological organization, as well as addressing issues at the tissue and cellular levels.

Hey guys, I've just recently started making videos on items that I have after not seeing them in searches on youtube.  I'm hoping that the information that I give may help others to be better informed on their buying decisions.   I'm just an avid gun and knife enthusiast and just like to share thoughts on items or weapons that I may have on hand.  I also love to travel so there are some videos of my travels to share with friends and family.   I'm by no means a professional reviewer of any type.  Just here to give honest and personal opinions on certain items I have.  I have many interests so my videos vary quite a bit, but I hope you enjoy the videos and leave comments. We are all here to learn, including myself and I would like to see the same level of respect given to everyone. Thanks.

Ed Dellis is the mechanical engineer who invented the custom-molded steering wheels you see in F1, IndyCar, NASCAR, ALMS, the Unlimiteds, and other sports car racing venues.  

His work in industrial ergonomics has helped prevent injuries for factory workers using assembly line tools involved in highly repetitive tasks that can lead to carpal tunnel syndrome and other RSI/CTD disorders.

As a racer, Dellis has won several driving championships, and his teaching at Skip Barber and the Bobby Rahal TrackTime Driving School is where he got to first share his knowledge of the Friction Circle.

His background as an artist helped him see how art and science combine when designing custom-molded handgrips.
